snippet.textDisplay: Used to like apple products years ago, first one i had was a g3, spent 1000 gbp roughly on a brand new g5, which was a big spend back then. The software was expensive for what I wanted to do, but I persisted, as apple had a rep back then for being solid machines, or so I thought. Literally the week the years warranty ran out the lcd screen decided to leak, and it killed the computer. There was an apple store in my city at the time, very posh it was, so I thought if i go see them, maybe they can offer help or a suggestion for getting me back up and running. No such luck, I basically got told to piss off by a miserable assistant. I had backed up my work for the year, but any work in progress was lost. I was so angry at apple for not offering any help, I was just under 1000 pounds out of pocket with a giant white dead thing sitting on my desk. It took me 6 months to finally throw the piece of shit out and I have never bought anything by that shitty company ever again. In a way im glad, because back then apple were on motorola chips and not intel, and I found the pc to be far more liberating. Im still pissed at them for taking my money and giving me a shit product in return which lasted a year, yes, still pissed, because i worked for that money, they didnt, they just gave me a sub standard piece of plastic shit and then told me to go fuck myself when it broke. Ill never buy an apple product again.

snippet.textDisplay: The processor is not the Xeon W-3275, it is the Xeon W-3275M. The difference is that the M-variant supports 2TB compared to 1TB on the Xeon W-3275. This is why Apple made the 1.5TB RAM only available for the 24- and 28-core, since both of them support 2TB of RAM in total. However, if you never wanted more than 1TB of RAM then it is just a useless expensive feature.

snippet.textDisplay: There's no doubt these things are a work of art and fantastic quality but the pricing on these is hideous. I also echo what people say about Dell's support. It is extremely good. Sometimes a little painful at the initial contact with a person on the phone but once the engineer is booked it's all totally painless. I have a Dell PC with 2 X eight core Xeons and 128 gig of RAM which I use in my Music recording studio. It has the option of a Thunderbolt 2 card and I needed to test if the Presonus Quantum would work so Dell sent me one to test on a sale or return basis. It worked fine so I bought it. The equivalent MAC would cost me about £8,000 and this PC is amazing, very quiet and totally reliable and trouble free. I am essentially a PC user but I do like Apple products (I have iPhone 11, various iPads etc), but they are just so incredibly over-priced, and their memory upgrade prices are ridiculous!

snippet.textDisplay:
Hmm maybe we could make a PC Tier Identifier based off how expensive mac accessories/cards/pre-installed Software are.
Compared to the CAD prices in the video, I used the US store and USD prices, even though myself I use GBP xD
Tier = $USD = Extra Accesories/Cards/Software = Apple MacBook you could get instead
S++ = $4000+ = Apple Afterburner Card + XDR Nano Texture Glass w Stand = Highest Prespec MacBookPro16", 2.4GHz, 8-core gen9 i9, 64GB RAM, 8GB VRAM
S+ = $3000 = Apple Afterburner Card + XDR Stand = Highest Prespec MacBook Pro 16" with a 2.4GHZ 8-core gen9 i9,16GB RAM, 4GB VRAM
S = $2000 = Apple Afterburner Card / XDR Nano Texture Glass w Stand = Highest Prespec MacBook Pro 13"
A = $1500 = 1 from B Tier + C Tier Software = Base Prespec MacBook Pro 13" with 1.4GHz 4-core gen8 i5 with 256GB Storage
B = $1000 = XDR Display Pro Stand / Upgrade to Nano Texture Glass = $100 short of a Base MacBook Air
C = $500 = Final Cut Pro X + Logic Pro X, PIS / Applecare+ for XDR Display
D = $400 = Case Wheels
E = $200 = XDR Display VESA Mount Adapter
F = $150- = Magic Keyboard with Numeric Keypad
and these don't even include the price of the NEW Cheesegrater or XDR Display, that's just how silly it is, heck you could buy a display without stand and nearly a Macbook Air, (short $100) for a XDR Display with a stand.
I would go as far as adding other mods (like how much they price [per SSD/RAM etc) too but that would go too far for this comment,
plus you could modify the Mac Pro itself with a lot of finagling for cheaper prices elsewhere.

Thanks Apple Tax!
and to people who say Macs aren't PCs, the main different between them is style, kernal and OS. PCs can have Mac/Linux/Windows OS, just Apple choose to not offer you to install MacOS on anything but an Apple Mac (unless you Hackintosh it yourself), heck the practises of not even stocking there Genius places with replacement parts (usually always offering to just exchange for a new part instead) really hurts the right for a consumer to repair there own product, so saying how much you can pay for any Mac and the support for repairing it is pretty bare is a lil sad. Yea they design it to not likely have problems making it east on the consumer but no company is perfect and, so stop treating Apple as perfect, they have done so many mistakes in the past. Sorry had to get that off my chest. (Heck I definitely don't mind Apple Products at all, heck I had a phew in the past but seeing no reason to ever get one again, but that's me, if I ever do it'll likely be something 2nd hand from now)

snippet.textDisplay: I've been in the VFX industry for almost 4 years, and Macs are not very popular at all. Most artists will probably be using Windows or Linux like you said. I recently switched to Linux and besides a few bugs the only stuff missing is from Adobe, which is a company that doesn't seem to really care about professionals anymore anyway. With this said, most professionals using Macs use them for color grading and in sound mixing/mastering studios, these are the markets I think Apple wants to make big bucks if we're talking about post-production. Without support for Nvidia (for renderers like Redshift, Octane...) it just doesn't make sense for companies to buy Macs starting at 6K. My workstation at work has 96GB of RAM and 2 Xeons, and they got it for less than half of the lowest-spec'd Mac Pro. So, unless you're a freelancer or you run a studio with very few workers, I don't think VFX artists will be using Mac Pros.

snippet.textDisplay: Thanks, Linus, for the fair review! I feel like a lot of people automatically roll their eyes at both the cost and the Apple branding when they see this thing, but you did a great job looking at it with an unbiased approach. I think a lot of people who jerk off over the "$1K Stand" meme don't realize this computer is not for them.

snippet.textDisplay: The point is, if you have more money than sense, this is the computer for you! If you want to save over $10k, build it yourself and run Windows. If you want to save another $20, build it yourself and run Linux.
